        <section class="col1 maincontent">
            
             
            <article class="article " xmlns:msxsl="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:xslt" xmlns:regExp="http://exslt.org/regular-expressions" xmlns:fb="http://www.facebook.com/2008/fbml"><div class="articlehead"><header><span></span><h1>Rheumatoid Arthritis at Work</h1></header><aside class="disclaimer"></aside><h2>People with this chronic illness perform all sorts of jobs. Here's how to navigate work life if you have rheumatoid arthritis. </h2><div class="bottom"><div class="byline">By <a href=/contributing-writers-and-editors.aspx>Connie Brichford</a></div><div class="reviewedby">Medically reviewed by <a href=/medical-reviewers.aspx>Pat F. Bass III, MD, MPH</a></div></div><div class="clear"></div></div><div id="video-player-top"></div><aside class="aside"></aside>
  <p>Rheumatoid arthritis is a chronic illness that affects all aspects of a person&#8217;s life, including work. But people with <a href="/health-report/rheumatoid-arthritis-management-guide.aspx">rheumatoid arthritis</a> are able to succeed in all kinds of professions. &#8220;With the medications we now have, there&#8217;s no reason they can&#8217;t do pretty much whatever they want,&#8221; says Elinor Mody, MD, director of the Women&#8217;s Orthopedic and Joint Disease Center at Brigham and Women&#8217;s Hospital in Boston. &#8220;I&#8217;ve had patients who fly planes, drive the subway. I&#8217;m always amazed at what they can do.&#8221; </p>
  <p>
    <strong>8 Ways to Cope With Rheumatoid Arthritis at Work </strong>
  </p>
  <p>There are many coping strategies that enable a person with rheumatoid arthritis to carry on with everyday work chores. Here are several strategies: </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Set up a professional evaluation. </strong>&#8220;Evaluation by an occupational therapist is beneficial to suggest ways to alleviate the impact of certain physical activities on pain and joint load,&#8221; says Dimitrios A. Pappas, MD, a post-doctoral fellow in the division of rheumatology at Johns Hopkins University. </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Go ergonomic. </strong>Ergonomic products minimize stress on your joints by encouraging comfortable, neutral posture as you work. &#8220;An ergonomic workstation is important for anyone, particularly for people with rheumatoid arthritis. Your keyboard at the right height, and an adjustable chair — all of those things are very important,&#8221; Mody says. Ergonomic keyboards will keep you from bending your wrists at awkward angles as you type; an adjustable chair will support your lower back. </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Move and stretch. </strong>Mody recommends taking time to get up, stretch, and move around. &#8220;I work a lot in the evenings seeing performances," says Sara Nash, a producer at a non-profit contemporary dance organization who was diagnosed with RA two years ago. "The late hours can be hard, and sitting in uncomfortable seats while watching shows is often difficult on my hips and knees." </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Ask for flex time. </strong>Depending upon the nature of your work, it might be possible to arrange a flexible schedule for those days when your rheumatoid arthritis is really flaring up. &#8220;I have had to leave work more than once when <a href="/health-report/rheumatoid-arthritis/rheumatoid-arthritis-and-fatigue.aspx">fatigue</a> has struck suddenly in the middle of the day,&#8221; Nash says. &#8220;Even though it is great to have this flexibility, it does mean that I have to play catch-up a lot.&#8221; </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Exercise. </strong>"It&#8217;s so important to make time to <a href="/health-report/rheumatoid-arthritis/ra-exercise-modifications.aspx">exercise</a>," Mody says. "Exercise has a protective effect against joint damage.&#8221; Taking good care of yourself in your off-hours not only leads to a healthier life, but it can help you stay comfortable, energized, and focused on the job. </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Prepare for bad days. </strong>&#8220;In some cases, patients will complete the FMLA (Family Medical Leave Act) paperwork and have it filed with their human resource department so that time off for appointments, flares, etc. [is] not held against them,&#8221; says Vicky Ruffing, RN, a nurse manager at Johns Hopkins Arthritis Center. </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Seek support. </strong>Nash's boss and close co-workers know about her rheumatoid arthritis and are understanding. &#8220;They have all been incredibly supportive. I find I am often more self-conscious and harder on myself than anyone else is,&#8221; says Nash. </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Educate others. </strong>Not all office environments are as supportive as Nash&#8217;s, and you may need to educate your bosses about rheumatoid arthritis before they&#8217;re willing to make the accommodations you need. Pappas and Ruffing recommend asking your <a href="/health-report/rheumatoid-arthritis/rheumatoid-arthritis-management/role-of-rheumatologist.aspx">health care team</a> to help with this process by writing letters of support. </p>
  <p>Rheumatoid arthritis can make some tasks more difficult, but there are ways you can make your job less taxing on your health. With the right equipment, a flexible schedule, and a little support, you can enjoy your job and take care of yourself at the same time. </p>
</article><div class="lastupdated" xmlns:msxsl="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:xslt" xmlns:regExp="http://exslt.org/regular-expressions" xmlns:fb="http://www.facebook.com/2008/fbml">
